Although Bill Gates did not take too many risks, he had many obstacles that stood in his way of his dream, even before he even had the dream of Microsoft. One such obstacle would be that his private elementary school did not have the money for the computers during the time that they were very expensive. To overcome this, his school had a fundraiser and was able to rent a year’s worth of time on the general electric computers. Although, within a few weeks, the year’s worth of time on the computers was up. Gate’s school then made a deal with Seattle-based Computer Center Corporation (CCC) for more time on the computers. Gates then got himself into trouble by hacking into the security of the computers and resetting the meters for the computers, and crashing them just for fun.  He was banned from using the computer for some weeks. After the ban was lifted, the CCC was beginning to suffer due to the weak security system, so they made a deal with Gate’s “gang” of hackers that if they found the bugs and report weaknesses of the system, that they could have unlimited use of the computers. In 1970 the CCC was run out of business by financial trouble. Although by now Paul Allen and Bill Gates had a new way to use computers, Allen’s father worked at the University of Washington, where they used the computers there. During Gate’s junior year in Lakeside, the administration offered himself and Allen a job to write a program that made the schedules. Over the summer of that year they did. It just so happened that Gates was put into classes with mostly girls the next year. In 1973, gates went to Harvard, but Allen, who certainly could have made it in as well decided to go a different route, even though the two were broken up by distance they kept in touch. When they talked, they talked about one day starting their own business. After Gate’s first year, Allen moved closer to Harvard. During Gate’s sophomore year, Allen decided to visit him. When Allen stopped at a convenient store, he saw a magazine that advertised a new computer that rivaled the current computers. Allen showed the magazine to Gate’s and they called and told the company Micro Instrumentation Telemetry Systems (MITS) that they had wrote a BASIC computer program that could be used on the new computers they were selling. They had not done this but MITS also had lied, they only had one prototype of the computer and it was lost in shipping. But MITS still asked them to come demonstrate the program in a few weeks time. Then Gates and Allen set out to make the program and make it work on the new computer, but this was hard because they did not have the new computer. After eight weeks, Gates and Allen showed the program to MITS and miraculously it worked perfectly. MITS then bought the rights for the program from Gates and Allen. Thus the software market was born. Bill waited till his junior year of high school to take a leave of absence from Harvard and went to create Microsoft.
